post_text:
District 207 will begin a new process for meal distribution next week. Please submit your order tonight (8/20) for meals next week.

This program is for any student. Learn more about the process in English and en Espanol. https://maine207.org/news/new-process-for-ordering-school-lunch-and-breakfast/

To purchase or receive a school breakfast or lunch, meals MUST be ordered in advance through a remote ordering and payment system titled MyMealOrder system. Meals orders need to be submitted by Thursday at midnight for the following week.

For students who qualify for free or reduced lunch and/or breakfast, parents MUST complete a NEW application for the 2020-21 school year which is available on the link above.

post_text:
After careful review and consideration, the district leadership team is recommending to the Board of Education that we slow the start of in-person school at the beginning of the year through the end of the first quarter.

Parents should know that “at home” learning will look much different than it looked in the spring as students will be required to attend class following their class schedule during their school day; students will earn grades as they would in a traditional classroom setting; students will be able to be on campus if they choose at times during “at home” learning; and the schools will hold in-person orientations for each grade level in the first few weeks of school to help students transition to this very different school year and learning environment.

There is a detailed plan available that shares key information and answers many parent questions: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Xu6EhJu2K4THxzlHxFcXd0LpPuNi9OKZLaZcBdUbX0A/edit?usp=sharing

post_text:
Dr. Laura Cook, Career Coordinator in District 207, recently earned the “Association for Career and Technical Education Region III Career Guidance Award” which qualifies her for the national award in the same category that will be awarded during the ACTE national conference in December.

This award recognizes guidance counselors and career development professionals who have made significant contributions to advocate, educate and communicate the value of CTE as a viable career option to a variety of audiences in their communities.

https://maine207.org/news/district-207-administrator-finalist-for-national-career-and-technical-education-award/

post_text: Maine West High School and Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) graduate Haripriya Mehta is opening up a virtual machine learning bootcamp for future engineers. The boot camp is a six-week course that will serve as an intro to machine learning class, similar to the one taught at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT). The boot camp teaches students coding concepts and is structured around building a machine learning project that they will get to present to their peers at the end. Apply by end of day on June 10. Read more: https://maine207.org/news/maine-west-graduate-offers-summer-bootcamp-for-high-school-students/

Village of Niles - Municipality
May 19 at 1:00 PM ·

Niles Makes It Possible to Get a Great Start in Life.

Dalal Hassane is proud to call Niles home. Daughter of Iraqi and Syrian immigrants and born and raised in Niles, Dalal finds many opportunities at Maine East High School to explore her passions. In Niles, where schools are first rate, every kid has the opportunity to succeed.

Learn more here:
https://www.loveniles.com/

#NilesMakesItPossible #LoveNiles

post_text: Thank you Maine Township HS District 207 Education Association for the $6,447.88 check for the Covid-19 fund. They collected money from teachers, teaching assistants, Maine Township High School District 207 retirees, administrative staff, former students and neighbors of association members! That donation puts the fund at more than $50,000. The fund has distributed $12,250 with another $5,000 scheduled to go out next week to the families most in need as we work to support families through what we believe will be an extended "stay at home" order in Illinois that is flattening the curve and saving lives.

post_text:
Both Maine East and Maine West High Schools recently held Poetry Contests and named school winners who will compete in the upcoming regional competition as part of the Poetry Out Loud, a national poetry recitation contest.

Heaven Moore-Brown won the Maine West competition and will compete at the regional competition. Anna Tooley was the first runner up and Meghna Pillai was the second runner up.

Congratulations also go out to Maine West's first poet laureate Jessica Schneider for her original poem "Only Once."

At Maine East, Emily Swoboda won the competition and will represent Maine East at regionals. The Maine East runners up were Rebecca Hurwitz and Bushra Khan.

The Chicagoland Regional competition will be held on Feb 18 at the Poetry Foundation building in Chicago.

On November 6, 2018, registered voters in Maine Township High School District 207 approved a ballot question to issue bonds to address facility improvements at Maine East, Maine South and Maine West high schools. For the past year, the District has been working diligently to ensure the upgrades and renovations would begin in the spring of 2020.

With all that work in the rearview mirror, the community can now see what the spaces within the schools will look like when the projects are completed as tentative renderings recently were shared with the Board of Education.

https://maine207.org/news/plans-being-finalized-for-construction-projects/

post_text:
When taxpayers in Maine Township High School District 207 approved the sale of bonds to replace outdated plumbing, electrical and mechanical systems, it was anticipated and shared with voters that the borrowing rate for the bonds would be at 4.54%. With two-thirds of the bonds sold recently, the rate for those bonds was much lower at 2.92%. The remaining bonds are estimated to be sold in 2022 and the total estimated savings to the taxpayers is $46.8 million in interest costs.

https://maine207.org/news/taxpayer-interest-cost-on-bonds-is-projected-to-be-46-million-less-than-originally-anticipated/

post_text: Thanks to the more than 60 Maine Township High School District 207 business partners that attended this week's Business Partner luncheon. post_text: A unique in the nation program called CLEAR has teams of educators learning together across Maine Township High School District 207 in Maine South High School, Maine East High School and Maine West High School to engage in action research to broaden/deepen the collective knowledge in the district in order to impact student learning. Teams presented their findings at iLEARN recently.
